Java Streams provide a modern and concise way to process collections of data. They support operations such as filtering, mapping, sorting, and aggregation using a functional programming approach.

1. Sum of Array
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
​
class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        int arr[] = { 30, 20, 10 };
        int sum = Arrays.stream(arr).sum();
        System.out.println(sum);
    }
}

Output
60
Explanation: Arrays.stream(arr) converts the array into an IntStream and The sum() method internally iterates over elements and returns their total..

2. Maximum in Array
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
​
class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        int arr[] = { 30, 20, 10 };
        int max = Arrays.stream(arr).max().getAsInt();
        System.out.println(max);
    }
}

Output
30
Explanation: max() returns an OptionalInt and getAsInt() retrieves the value (array must be non-empty).

